{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492851"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.11,0.31,0.17,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1169"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1363"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17255"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old man is admitted to hospital with an episode of alcohol-related pancreatitis. This is judged to be a mild episode and the patient is given pain relief, enteral nutrition and IV fluids. His symptoms improve and he is discharged home two days later. However, he is readmitted three days later as his abdominal pain has worsened and he feels nauseated. His blood pressure is 132/80, pulse 94/min and temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is some epigastric tenderness. He is kept on nourishing fluids and is receiving intravenous fluids at 2L/24 hrs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA full blood count and serum biochemistry are arranged (Image 1, 2). His procalcitonin level is 0.03 ng/ml (\u0026lt;0.1)\u003Cstrong\u003E. \u003C/strong\u003EA triple phase CT shows interstitial oedema in the body and tail of the pancreas with some fluid collection around the gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to an anti-emetic, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current plan of management","Increase rate of intravenous fluid administration","Broad spectrum antibiotics","Stop all oral intake","Fine needle aspiration of pancreatic tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe focus of this question is whether the current plan of management needs to be changed. Whilst complications such as pancreatic necrosis and abscess formation must be considered, there is little evidence at this stage to support the development of such a complication. He does not show any signs of infection. The laboratory values and the procalcitonin lean against an infective process and there is no place for antibiotics. While the neutrophil count is elevated, this elevation is only slight and is likely to be because of the recent acute pancreatitis. Prophylactic antibiotics are not indicated in acute pancreatitis since there is little evidence of their benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s vital signs are within normal range and there are no signs or symptoms that suggest dehydration. Therefore, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in the rate of fluid administration \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated. He should be \u003Cstrong\u003Emanaged on the current treatment plan\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe information provided in the stem does not suggest that there needs to be any change in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral intake should only be stopped if the patient cannot tolerate anything by mouth and was vomiting. Since this patient has abdominal pain and nausea but no vomiting, \u003Cstrong\u003Estopping all oral intake \u003C/strong\u003Eis not going to be of benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E fine needle aspiration of pancreatic tissue \u003C/strong\u003Emight be indicated if infection or an abscess was suspected. There is nothing to suspect such a problem with this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with acute pancreatitis can be managed with supportive care alone."],"references":["Mederos MA, Reber HA, Girgis MD.  Acute Pancreatitis A Review. JAMA. 2021; 325:382-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33496779/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19298"},{"type":"media","id":"19299"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19298"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/676e8c85-7116-4206-a86e-20d613a2506f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/676e8c85-7116-4206-a86e-20d613a2506f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":248}},{"type":"media","id":"19299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19299"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2ee4edfb-0601-4b3d-bb3f-f31d9d7d607b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2ee4edfb-0601-4b3d-bb3f-f31d9d7d607b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":305}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54636